{
    "identity": "nprot-279",
    "title": "Detection of O<sub>2</sub><sup>.-</sup> production by chemiluminescence \\(CL) assay",
    "content": [
        {
            "header": "Introduction",
            "content": "Hemoglobin is auto-oxidized from ferrous-hemoglobin to ferric hemoglobin \\(methemoglobin, metHb) with the production of H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>.   H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub> initiates the catalytic cycle between the ferric \\(HbFeIII) and ferryl \\(HbFeIV) hemes, thus activating the pseudoperoxidase activity of metHb, which eliminates the H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>, producing the superoxide<sup>1</sup>.  The chemiluminescence \\(CL) of Cypridina luciferin analog indicates the generation of O<sub>2</sub><sup>&#x2022;-</sup> or singlet oxygen, but not that of ozone, hydroxyl radicals or H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub><sup>2</sup>.  To further confirm that the ROS species produced by metHb and indicated by CLA-CL is superoxide anions but not singlet oxygen, superoxide dismutase \\(SOD) is applied as a diagnostic confirmation of superoxide anion production."
        },
        {
            "header": "Procedure",
            "content": "The pseudoperoxidase activity is measured as described\n2\n, with modifications. \r\n\n\n1. Add metHb into a substrate mixture containing 5.3 \u03bcM of CLA and 3.3 mM of H\n2\nO\n2\nin 150 \u03bcl of PBS \\(pH 7.4).  \r\n  2.  Continuously monitor the chemiluminescence, indicated by relative luminescence units \\(rlu), at one reading per s, for 1 min, with Sirius luminometer \\(Berthold Detection Systems GmbH, Germany). \r\n  3.  The pseudoperoxidase activity of the metHb is designated as the relative luminescence units per second \\(rlu/s). \r\n  4. To prove that the ROS species indicated by CLA-CL is superoxide anions, 3 Units/ml of SOD is applied to specifically quench the superoxide anions."
        },
        {
            "header": "Anticipated Results",
            "content": "The read out of CLA-LA varies from 10<sup>5</sup>-10<sup>7</sup> rlu/s depending on the concentration of the metHb and the H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub> as the substrate as well as that of CLA as the indicator."
        },
        {
            "header": "References",
            "content": "1. Alayash, A. I. Hemoglobin-based blood substitutes: oxygen carriers, pressor    agents, or oxidants? _Nat Biotechnol_. **17**, 545-549 \\(1999). \r\n  2. Kawano, T., Pinontoan, R., Hosoya, H. &amp; Muto, S. Monoamine-dependent production of reactive oxygen species catalyzed by pseudoperoxidase activity of human hemoglobin. _Biosci Biotechnol Biochem_. **66**, 1224-1232 \\(2002)."
        }
    ],
